    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="121"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Roosevelt Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to Prime
                        Minister <persName type="to">Churchill</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d121fn1">Sent by the White House Map Room to the United
                        States Naval Attaché, London, via Navy channels, after Roosevelt had
                        approved the text. See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_189">p.
                            189</ref>, fn. 5.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hyde Park</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-05">5 September
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Number 619, personal and secret, from the President for the Prime Minister.</p>
                <p>Replying to your 779,<note n="2" xml:id="d121fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_188">p. 188</ref>.</note>
                        780<note n="3" xml:id="d121fn3">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note> and 781,<note n="4" xml:id="d121fn4"
                        >Not printed herein. See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_188"
                            >p. 188</ref>, fn. 3.</note> I am informed by my Office of Military
                    Intelligence that the fighting <gloss target="#t_Poles1">Poles</gloss> have
                    departed from War saw and that the Germans are now in full control.</p>
                <p>The problem of relief for the <gloss target="#t_Poles1">Poles</gloss> in Warsaw
                    has therefore unfortunately been solved by delay and by German action and there
                    now appears to be nothing we can do to assist them.</p>
                <p>I have long been deeply distressed by our inability to give adequate assistance
                    to the heroic defenders of Warsaw and I hope that we may together still be able
                    to help Poland be among the victors in this war with the Nazis.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Roosevelt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
